{"type":"message","id":"3cc24a53","parentId":"a53a6a61","timestamp":"2026-04-14T07:58:59.132Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`js-yaml` is in the root `node_modules`, not in the renderer's own `node_modules`. The renderer process in Vite can't directly import from the root `node_modules`. I need to check how Vite is configured to resolve modules.\n\nActually, looking at the vite.config.ts:\n```js\nresolve: {\n  alias: {\n    '@': resolve(__dirname, 'src/renderer/src'),\n  },\n},\n```\n\nThere's no alias for `js-yaml`. So I can't directly `import yaml from 'js-yaml'` in the renderer code.\n\nOption: Use the main process IPC to parse YAML (have the main process's `aiService.ts` or a new IPC handler do the YAML parsing).\n\n\nI could set up an IPC handler in the main process to handle YAML parsing, but that adds unnecessary overhead. Let me reconsider—`js-yaml` is actually browserifiable and could work in the renderer. The real issue is that Vite's module resolution doesn't include the root `node_modules` by default for renderer code. Since `factExtractor.ts` already imports from `'../db'`, I need to check how other renderer services are handling module imports.\n\nLooking at the `package.json`, there's no explicit `dependencies` section—everything in `node_modules` is a dev dependency. That means `js-yaml` won't be bundled unless I add it to `dependencies`, and Vite won't resolve it from the renderer's context unless I configure it to do so.\n\nThe pragmatic move is to handle YAML parsing through IPC in the main process instead, which already has access to `js-yaml`. I'll skip bundling it separately and just use an IPC call for parsing and serialization.","thinkingSignature":"0042b047695be81c003a211dffa600f176fac59f14ab1bafb65014fb8e8c1b27"},{"type":"text","text":"`js-yaml` 不在 renderer 的依赖里，不能直接 import。最稳妥的方案：**让 main process 处理 YAML 读写**，通过 IPC 调用。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_pfi5hq8o2jsq_1","name":"exec","argum