{"type":"message","id":"ee08269f","parentId":"03f6ef54","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:37:32.840Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me also check the `TOOLS` array in bash. In bash 3.x (macOS default), arrays defined with `TOOLS=(...)` and accessed with `${TOOLS[@]}` should work. But in this case, the syntax `TOOLS=( \"personality.js:ISTJ\" ... )` should be fine.Actually, there's another issue - bash associative arrays and `for entry in \"${TOOLS[@]}\"` requires bash 4+. This should be fine on Linux (bash 5+).Also, I need to check the `aiModels` check - I'm using `$AI_MODELS` which is the result of grep which is multi-line. When I do `echo \"$AI_MODELS\" | grep -q \"$m\"`, it should work. \n\nLet me just run the script now and see what happens.","thinkingSignature":"166d2c2995bf792e270392789f7d26054a68e66b9dc79b7d44b0b98afd71947c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0ilz6otsfrfv_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"bash /mnt/d/aafuzhi/axs/auto-review.sh 2>&1","timeout":300}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":124384,"output":229,"cacheRead":19262,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":143875,"cost":{"input":0.0373152,"output":0.0002748,"cacheRead":0.0011557199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03874572}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776163044156,"responseId":"062d4be462b852d06a657248fed763cf"}}
