{"type":"message","id":"21b5162b","parentId":"676b81f1","timestamp":"2026-04-14T12:12:52.604Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, `signAndEditExecutable` might not be the right config option. Let me think. For electron-builder, the option to skip code signing is `windows.signAndEditExecutable: false`. But actually, for the `portable` target, it shouldn't need winCodeSign anyway. The issue might be that electron-builder always tries to use winCodeSign for Windows builds.\n\nActually, looking at the error more carefully - it's trying to download `winCodeSign-2.6.0.7z`. This is used by electron-builder to edit the executable resources (set the app name, icon, etc.) on Windows. Since we're not using an icon, we can try to skip this step.\n \nI should try setting `windows.signDlls: false` to see if that prevents the winCodeSign download, though I'm not entirely certain that's the right flag. Alternatively, I could look into using an electron-builder mirror to bypass the download issue entirely.\n\nLooking at the documentation, `electronDownload` controls the Electron binary downloads but not the builder tools themselves. For those, I'd need to configure `ELECTRON_BUILDER_BINARIES_MIRROR`. Since I'm already using npmmirror for Electron downloads, I should check if that same mirror has the builder binaries available.\n\nThe core issue is that even though I set up the Electron mirror, electron-builder still attempts to fetch `winCodeSign` from GitHub. I need to find the correct configuration option to redirect those tool downloads—either through an environment variable or a config setting—to point to a working mirror like npmmirror.\n\nLooking at the electron-builder documentation, I can set `electronDownload` to use npmmirror for Electron itself, but I should also check if there's a separate `winCodeSign` mirror or if I can disable code signing altogether since the portable .exe doesn't require it. The portable target might not need winCodeSign at all, so I could try running with just the portable configuration and see if that avoids the failed download attempt. So the `winCodeSign` error actually occurs before the portable target finishes—it's trying to edit the executable during the packaging phase. Even though portable creates a standalone exe, electron-builder still attempts to modify the original executable first, which requires winCodeSign.\n\nI could try setting up a mirror for the builder binaries, or I could experiment with `nsis` instead, which might handle portable differently. Let me check what happens if I disable the executable signing and editing step entirely.\n\nActually, I realize the issue—I don't need a custom icon since the build directory doesn't exist anyway, so I should just remove the icon configuration from the Windows settings rather than trying to work around the winCodeSign download failure. I need to verify the correct electron-builder configuration option for disabling the Windows executable signing step, since `signAndEditExecutable` might not be the right property name.","thinkingSignature":"501708cae69bf1c9db47847669d2a3717f0755f3b51a26b51f510439f89dbb57"},{"type":"text","text":"需要检查正确的配置项：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qibtl8lwio9u_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"signAndEdit\\|signDll\\|rcedit\" /mnt/d/aafuzhi/axs/node_modules/electron-builder/lib/*.js 2>/dev/null | grep -v \"node_modules\" | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":75951,"output":666,"cacheRead":19262,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":95879,"cost":{"input":0.022785299999999998,"output":0.0007991999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0011557199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.024740219999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776168744954,"responseId":"062d6229dc11720db469a1d2e719949c"}}
