{"type":"message","id":"835cbeae","parentId":"6e29fc27","timestamp":"2026-04-14T12:24:36.095Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The file content looks correct - it shows `.replace(/\\/g, '/')` and `.replace(/\\/+/g, '/')`. But wait, I can see in the file that it says:\n```\n    .replace(/\\/g, '/')\n    .replace(/\\/+/g, '/')\n```\n\nThese ARE correct! The `replace(/\\/g, '/')` is correct - it's a regex that matches a forward slash. But wait, that's not what I want. I want to replace backslashes with forward slashes.\n\nActually, looking at the file content:\n- `.replace(/\\/g, '/')` - this would match forward slashes and replace with forward slash (nonsense)\n\n\n- `.replace(/\\/+/g, '/')` - this would match one or more forward slashes and replace with one forward slash (also nonsense)\n\nThe file is showing the correct content but my edit tool might have been misinterpreting it. The original edit I made might have been corrupted. Let me just check what esbuild actually says the error is. The error says line 11:23 - let me count the lines in the file. Line 11 in the current file would be `.replace(/\\/g, '/')`. At column 23... that doesn't align with a forward slash replacement being invalid.\n\nLooking at the actual line numbers from the error output - lines 9-12 contain the parts array, join, and the two replace calls. Line 10's `.join('/')` is fine, but line 11's `.replace(/\\/g, '/')` is trying to use a regex with an escaped forward slash, which doesn't make sense. The backslash in the regex pattern is being interpreted as an escape character, making the pattern invalid.\n\nThe issue is that when I wrote `replace(/\\/g, '/')` in the source, the `\\/` should represent a forward slash in the regex, but the way it's being parsed is causing an \"Unterminated string literal\" error at line 11:23. The backslash is escaping the forward slash in a way that breaks the regex literal syntax. I need to figure out what actually got written to the file. The edit command is showing me that `/\\/g` was replaced with `/\\\\/g`, which means the original regex pattern had a forward slash that got escaped as `\\/`. But that escape sequence itself is malformed in regex syntax, which is why esbuild is choking on it. The file clearly contains `/\\/g` at that position, so something in my edit introduced extra escaping that shouldn't be there. I'm realizing the edit might have mangled the regex escaping when writing to the file. Let me try a simpler approach—just concatenating the path parts with forward slashes and handling the cleanup with a straightforward replace operation, rather than trying to wrangle complex regex patterns that are getting double-escaped.","thinkingSignature":"1911dd3a42d2be601153bcb8005a6cc94f72468662ff2200fe8ab67697dc5f1c"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_kr4xoszahzv5_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/mnt/d/aafuzhi/axs/src/renderer/src/components/OutlineTree.tsx","edits":[{"oldText":"    .replace(/\\/g, '/')\n    .replace(/\\/+/g, '/')","newText":"    .replace(/\\/g, '/')\n    .replace(/\\/+/g, '/')"}]}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":87026,"output":698,"cacheRead":19262,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":106986,"cost":{"input":0.0261078,"output":0.0008376,"cacheRead":0.0011557199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.02810112}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776169455083,"responseId":"062d64ee69e074204fe4893613eba173"}}
